Variation in GP referrals to acute medicine in Greater Glasgow & Clyde

Allan Cameron, Marcus Lyall, Iain Keith, Claire Gordon, Daniel Beckett

17 May 2018

Introduction

This document describes a method to identify and quantify variation in referral rates from primary care to acute medicine, with the aim of identifying and sharing best referral practice. It grew out of discussions between Marcus Lyall, Dan Beckett, Claire Gordon, Iain Keith and Allan Cameron.

The manuscript was written in R Markdown before being rendered in its current form. R Markdown is a simple mark-up language that facilitates transparent and reproducible research [1]. It is written as a plain text file that incorporates the article, formatting, and code used to carry out the analysis. This way any plots, tables or inline results are rendered directly from the included code when the document is compiled. The hope is that this will allow easier regional collaboration.

To make the manuscript easier to follow for those without knowledge of the R language, the code is hidden by default, but can be shown in part or in entirety by using the grey code buttons on the right of this page. For those familiar with R, comments are left visible in the code to explain the purpose of each section.

Motivation

Large numbers of referrals to medical receiving can lead to undesirable patient experiences, including increased waits for assessment, longer waits for beds and delays in medical care [24].

Whilst the majority of referrals to acute medicine are appropriate and most result in hospital admission, anecdotally there are occasions when patients who are referred for assessment could have been managed in the community without consuming secondary care resources. GP practices that refer a large proportion of such patients could be described as having a relatively profligate referral pattern. Conversely, those who refer very few such patients might be described as having a parsimonious pattern.

This is not to say that all referrals that do not end in admission are inappropriate; on the contrary, the majority are appropriate. Most of the patients who are discharged directly from medical assessment units required urgent investigations or treatments which could have only been carried out in a secondary care setting.

However, with resources in secondary care being stretched to the limits of what is safe, any method that might reduce unnecessary referrals should be explored as a potential route to conserve resources. For this reason, it would be useful to know whether there are policies or practices that tend to reduce unnecessary referrals from primary care. To be objective about this, it is necessary to determine which GP practices have relatively parsimonious and which have profligate referral patterns.

Methods

The raw number of patients referred by each practice will largely be determined by the size of that practice, but will also be affected by the age, health, geography and demographics of its population. In reality there are too many confounding variables to say what part referral practices play in referral numbers by modelling expected numbers of referrals from a given practice then measuring how far actual referrals deviate from this.

However, it is straightforward to count the number of patients referred from each practice, then calculate the proportion who were admitted. This has the benefit of automatically taking practice size and demographics into account; for GPs with the same referral practices, the proportion admitted should hold steady regardless of size and patient mix.

Another way to look at this is to assume that for any GP practice, there will be a number of patients who require admission, and that the number of referrals for patients who do not need admission will be directly proportional to this.

The proportion admitted gives a surrogate measure of the positive predictive value (PPV) of a referral in predicting admission. Parsimonious referrals will have a higher PPV than profligate referrals.

We can therefore simply compare each practices admission proportion to the total proportion of referrals admitted. In order to take sample size into account and avoid type 1 errors, this should be done with a funnel plot, as the proportion admitted is expected to vary widely due to chance between the GP practices with small numbers of referrals.

Any practices that lie outside the 95% confidence interval can thus be identified, and their impact on overall referrals estimated by comparing the number of their referrals who were discharged to the expected number of discharges given the number of admissions the practice generated.

Once GP practices with an apparently high impact are identified, we can explore reasons for their referral patterns by comparing closely co-located practices with different referral patterns, examining their patients demographics using data available in the public domain from ISD Scotland, then examining discharge diagnoses and individual case note reviews.

Data preparation

The minimal dataset required for this analysis is the GP practice for each referral, and the outcome of that referral. For our purposes, only an active decision to discharge should count as a discharge. Deaths and transfers should be considered admissions, whereas patients who leave before treatment is complete are excluded from analysis.

This analysis uses several external R packages: httr to obtain data resources from the internet, readxl to load data from spreadsheet format, magrittr, to make the code more readable, and ggplot2 to produce the plots [5,6]. It also uses the knitr and kableExtra packages to render the current document. These packages are installed automatically if not present.

# This is a simple function that takes a vector of names of external libraries.
# It checks whether each library is installed, and if not installs it.
# It then loads the libraries into memory

getLibraries <- function(x) {
  for (i in seq_along(x)) {
  if (!any(installed.packages()[, 1] %in% x[i])) {
    install.packages(x[i])
  }
  eval(parse(text = paste0("library(", x[i], ")")))
  }
}

# We can now load the specific libraries we need into memory and remove the getLibraries function
getLibraries(c("magrittr", "ggplot2", "readxl", "httr", "knitr", "kableExtra"))
rm(getLibraries)

# This function allows tables to be displayed in a standard format
displayTable <- function(x) {
  x %>% 
  t() %>%
  kable("html", align = "c") %>% 
  kable_styling(bootstrap_options = c("striped", "hover"),
                full_width = FALSE, position = "left")
}

Data loading and cleaning

The data in this example come directly from Trakcare. An entire year worth of attendances to unscheduled care across Greater Glasgow & Clyde are loaded, one week at a time, from a secure local server. The weekly spreadsheets are large, each containing 35 fields on around 10,000 patients.

This one years worth of the data are loaded in sequentially and trimmed to only include data from the three main medical assessment units, and only to include the two necessary fields. This effectively anonymises individual patients.

# This defines the absolute path to all the spreadsheet files
# We start on the 44th file of the directory because this is the first week that contains
# data from all sites of interest. We need 52 weeks in total.
filenames <-
"\\\\XGGC.SCOT.NHS.UK\\GGCData\\FolderRedirects\\GRI5\\cameral931\\My Documents\\Documents\\EDLs\\full data\\" %>%
paste0(dir(.)[44:(44 + 51)])

# This loop reads the files and selects only the completed episodes occurring in medical
# assessment units. On the last loop it joins all the dataframes together to generate
# a 'master' data frame
for (i in seq_along(filenames)) {
  if (!exists("framelist")) {
    framelist <- list()
  }
  framelist[[i]] <-
    as.data.frame(readxl::read_excel(filenames[i])) %>%
    subset(
      grepl("(Assessment Unit)|(CDU)", .$Department) &
        !grepl("(Surgical)|(VOLMAU)", .$Department) &
        .$VisitStatus == "D"
    )
  if (i == length(filenames)) {
    master <- do.call("rbind", framelist)
    rm(framelist)
    rm(filenames)
  }
}
rm(i)

# This chunk retains only capital letters, which gives a useful abbreviation for hospital names
master$Hospital %<>% as.character %>%
  strsplit("([[:lower:]])|( )") %>%
  lapply(function(x)
    paste0(x, collapse = "")) %>%
  unlist %>%
  as.factor

# Extract minimal dataset for anonymous analysis
db <- master[c("GPPractice", "Hospital", "DischargeType")]
names(db) <- c("GPcode", "Site", "DischargeType")

# Covert data types
db$GPcode %<>% as.character
db$DischargeType %<>% as.factor

Finally, we need to add a column that records in a binary fashion whether a patient was admitted to hospital. We also change the GP practice codes to arbitrary numbers so that we can publish results without identifying particular GP practices.

#Parse Discharge Type into logical vector with NA for IRDs
db$Admitted <- !grepl("01", db$DischargeType)
db$Admitted[grepl("04", db$DischargeType)] <- NA

#Create non-public  GP lookup table to de-anonymise GP practices if required
GPlookup <- db$GPcode %>% as.factor %>% levels
db$GPcode %<>% as.factor %>% as.numeric
master$levs <- match(master$GPPracticeAddress, GPlookup)

We will also require demographic data from each GP practice, as well as patient-level data on deprivation. The latter can be found by cross-referencing each patients postcode to the Scottish Index of Multiple Deprivation (SIMD), which is available for each Scottish postcode. Both sets of data are available on the ISD Scotland website as spreadsheet files. These files can be directly read into R.

# Get SIMD data from ISD
# Warning! This is a large data set and will take a long time to download and load to memory
simd <-
  read.csv(
  "http://www.isdscotland.org/Products-and-Services/GPD-Support/Deprivation/SIMD/_docs/SIMD_2016/postcode_2017_2_simd2016.csv"
  ) %>%
  extract(c("pc7", "simd2016rank")) %>%
  set_names(c("postcode", "rank"))
  
  # Get GP Practice data from ISD: needs to save the file locally first, removes it once read
  writeBin(
  GET(
  "http://www.isdscotland.org/Health-Topics/General-Practice/Workforce-and-Practice-Populations/_docs/Practice_ListSize_Apr2018.xlsx"
  )[[6]],
  "GPlist.xlsx"
  )
  GPlist <- as.data.frame(read_xlsx("GPlist.xlsx", range = "A7:L957"))
  file.remove("GPlist.xlsx")
  
  # Assign all patients an SIMD ranking by postcode
  master$simd <- simd$rank[match(master$Postcode, simd$postcode)]

This gives us our cleaned data set. Our anonymous minimal data set is quite large, containing 52950 rows of four variables. The first few rows are shown below.

Analysis

The analysis itself is straightforward. We just count the number of referrals and admissions from each GP practice. We also need to remove those practices whose only referrals self-discharged. We can then calculate the proportion of referrals from each practice that are admitted to each site, and each sites overall admission rate.

sites <- list()
for (i in seq_along(levels(db$Site))) {
  tl <- list()
  tdb <- subset(db, Site == levels(Site)[i])
  tl$GPRefs <- tapply(tdb$Admitted, tdb$GPcode, function(x) {length(x[!is.na(x)])})
  tl$GPAdmits <- tapply(tdb$Admitted, tdb$GPcode, function(x) {length(which(x))}) %>%
  subset(tl$GPRefs != 0)
  tl$GPRefs %<>% subset(. != 0)
  tl$GPProps <- tl$GPAdmits / tl$GPRefs
  tl$Av <- tdb$Admitted %>% as.numeric %>% mean(na.rm = T)
  sites[[i]] <- tl
  names(sites)[i] <- levels(db$Site)[i]
  rm(tdb)
}

This allows us to create a funnel plot for each site, to which we add a mean line and 95% confidence intervals based on the binomial distribution [7]. There are a few outliers on our funnel plots; to find and quantify them, we look for those which have proportions which fall outside the confidence intervals and plot them on the graph in red (profligate) or green (parsimonious):

for (i in seq_along(sites)) {
  tl <- sites[[i]]
  tl$mins <- qbinom(0.025, 1:max(tl$GPRefs), tl$Av) / 1:max(tl$GPRefs)
  tl$maxs <- qbinom(0.975, 1:max(tl$GPRefs), tl$Av) / 1:max(tl$GPRefs)
  tl$logitmins <- log(tl$mins / (1 - tl$mins))
  tl$logitmaxs <- log(tl$maxs / (1 - tl$maxs))
  tl$ss <- seq(1, length(tl$logitmins), 5)
  tl$logitmins <- tl$logitmins[tl$ss]
  tl$logitmaxs <- tl$logitmaxs[tl$ss]
  tl$CI <- data.frame(xmin = tl$logitmins, xmax = tl$logitmaxs,y = tl$ss)
  tl$CI <- tl$CI[-(1:2),] #removes infinite values
  tl$df <- data.frame(practice = names(tl$GPRefs),
                      Referrals = tl$GPRefs,
                      LogRefs = log(tl$GPRefs),
                      Admissions = tl$GPAdmits,
                      Proportion = tl$GPProps,
                      logit = log(tl$GPProps / (1 - tl$GPProps)),
                      ExtraRefs = tl$GPRefs - (tl$GPAdmits / tl$Av),
                      Effect = abs(tl$GPRefs - (tl$GPAdmits / tl$Av)),
                      row.names = 1:length(tl$GPRefs)
                      )
  tl$df %<>% subset(abs(.$logit) < 100)
  sites[[i]] <- tl
  rm(tl)
  
  print(
    ggplot(data = sites[[i]]$df, aes(x = logit, y = Referrals)
    ) + geom_point(aes(colour = ExtraRefs, size = Effect)
    ) + geom_vline(aes(xintercept = log(sites[[i]]$Av / (1 - sites[[i]]$Av))), linetype = 2
    ) + scale_color_gradient2(low = "green", mid = "grey75", high = "red"
    ) + geom_smooth(
      data = sites[[i]]$CI,
      aes(x = xmax, y = y),
      method = 'loess',
      span = 3000 / sum(sites[[i]]$df$Referrals),
      se = F,
      colour = "#AABBFF"
    ) + geom_smooth(
      data = sites[[i]]$CI,
      aes(x = xmin, y = y),
      method = "loess",
      span = 3000 / sum(sites[[i]]$df$Referrals),
      se = F,
      colour = "#AABBFF"
    ) + theme(legend.position = ("none")) + labs(
      x = "Log odds of admission",
      y = "Total referrals",
      title = paste(
        "Figure",
        i,
        ": GP practice referrals to medical receiving at",
        names(sites)[i]
      ),
      subtitle = "Size & colour represent effect of referral practice on receiving numbers"
    )
  )
}

Finally, we can summarise our data by calculating which GP practices fall beneath the 95th centile and are therefore most profligate. Similarly, we can list the parsimonious practices by finding the subset above the 95th centile.

# Calculate the excess referrals for each outlying practice
totalExcess <- 0
for (i in seq_along(sites)) {
  tl <- sites[[i]]
  tl$OR <- which(tl$GPProps < tl$mins[tl$GPRefs])
  tl$Excess <- tl$GPRefs[tl$OR] - (tl$GPAdmits[tl$OR] / tl$Av)
  cat("Profligate GP referral practices referring to ",
    names(sites)[i],
    ":\n",
    paste(names(tl$GPRefs[tl$OR]), collapse = ",  "),
    "\n\n",
    sep = ""
  )
  totalExcess <- totalExcess + sum(tl$Excess)
  tl$UR <- which(tl$GPProps > tl$maxs[tl$GPRefs])
  tl$Shortfall <- tl$GPRefs[tl$UR] - (tl$GPAdmits[tl$UR] / tl$Av)
  cat("Parsimonious GP referral practices referring to ",
    names(sites)[i],
    ":\n",
    paste(names(tl$GPRefs[tl$UR]), collapse = ",  "),
    "\n\n",
    sep = ""
  )
  tl$OR <- master[which(master$levs %in% as.numeric(names(tl$OR))), ]
  tl$UR <- master[which(master$levs %in% as.numeric(names(tl$UR))), ]
  sites[[i]] <- tl
  rm(tl)
}

Case study

It would be enlightening to examine a single sites data as a case study in how this analysis might be put to use. Ideally, to minimise the confounding effects of distance from the hospital and demographics, we should like to find two GP practices that are closely co-located but have apparently different referral patterns. One of the interesting results from Glasgow Royal Infirmarys data is that there are two instances where a single health centre each has two GP practices that appear to have opposite referral patterns.

We can use the data from ISD to compare these GP practices.

Firstly, we select one of these pairs and extract all the patients referred by them from our master data frame. We can then compare the admission rates.

URGP <- sites[[1]]$UR$GPPracticeAddress %>% 
  table %>% 
  sort %>%
  names %>%
  rev %>%
  extract(10)
ORGP <- sites[[1]]$OR$GPPracticeAddress %>% 
  table %>% 
  sort %>%
  names %>%
  rev %>%
  extract(12)
master$overunder <- character(length(master[,1]))
master$overunder[master$GPPracticeAddress == ORGP] <- "Over"
master$overunder[master$GPPracticeAddress == URGP] <- "Under"
master$overunder[master$overunder == ""] <- NA
master$overunder %<>% factor
cdb <- master %>% subset(!is.na(.$overunder))
cdb$Admitted <- !grepl("01", cdb$DischargeType)
cdb$Admitted[grepl("04", cdb$DischargeType)] <- NA
counts <- table(cdb$Admitted, cdb$overunder)
colnames(counts) <- c("Practice 1", "Practice 2")
row.names(counts) <- c("Discharged", "Admitted")
displayTable(t(counts))
Practice 1 Practice 2
Discharged 61 38
Admitted 55 94

There is a clear discrepancy in admission rates, with Practice 1 having an admission rate of 47.4% (95% CI 38.1 - 56.9%) compared to Practice 2s rate of 71.2% (95% CI 62.6 - 78.6%), p=0.00023.

We can examine the patient characteristics to look for patterns.

# Create a table of gender, age and SIMD differences between practices
gendertab <- table(cdb$Gender, cdb$overunder) %>% 
  {c( 100 * .[1,]/(.[1,] + .[2,]), chisq.test(.)$p.value)}

agetab <-
cdb$Age %>% 
  as.numeric %>%
  tapply(cdb$overunder, mean) %>%
  c(t.test(as.numeric(cdb$Age[cdb$overunder == "Over"]),
           as.numeric(cdb$Age[cdb$overunder == "Under"]))$p.value)

simdtab <- 
  cdb$simd %>% 
  tapply(cdb$overunder, function(x) median(x, na.rm = T)) %>%
  c(wilcox.test(cdb$simd[cdb$overunder == "Over"],
                cdb$simd[cdb$overunder == "Under"])$p.value)

demographics <- rbind(gendertab, agetab, simdtab)
colnames(demographics) <- c("Practice 1", "Practice 2", "p value")
row.names(demographics) <- c("Percentage female", "Mean Age", "Median SIMD")
displayTable(t(signif(demographics, 3)))
Practice 1 Practice 2 p value
Percentage female 50.4 48.9 0.9050
Mean Age 60.1 63.4 0.1800
Median SIMD 575.0 233.0 0.0158

It appears that there is a significant difference in deprivation between the two practices; although the median SIMD is in the bottom decile for both practices, practice 2 (with a parsimonious referral pattern) has a lower SIMD. However, this does not appear to be a major contributing cause of the difference in referrals, since there is no significant difference in SIMD between patients admitted and patients discharged (418 in admitted patients versus 568 in those discharged, p=0.158).

We can model the impact of GP practice, SIMD, age and sex on admissions using logistic regression:

# Runs a multiple logistic regression on available variables
# Obtains the standard coefficient table and makes it presentable
glm(Admitted ~ as.numeric(Age) + Gender + simd + overunder, data = cdb, family = binomial) %>%
  summary %>% 
  extract("coefficients") %>% 
  unlist %>% 
  matrix(ncol = 4) %>% 
  as.table %>% 
  `colnames<-`(c("coefficient", "Standard error", "z value", "p value")) %>%
  `row.names<-`(c("Intercept", "Age", "Gender male", "SIMD", "Practice 2")) %>% 
  t %>% 
  displayTable

The important numbers to look at here are the p values in the last column. These show that age and GP practice are significant independent predictors of likelihood of discharge from the assessment unit, whereas gender and deprivation level have no discernible effect.

Given that there was no significant age difference between patients referred from the practice, that the practices are equidistant from the hospital, and that the small difference in deprivation did not explain the difference in admission rates, it seems reasonable to examine case mix to determine whether this is the cause of the difference.

The striking differences are in discharges following referrals for chest pain and headache. Given what we saw earlier with regards the underlying demographics, it seems very likely that this difference is due to different thresholds for referral by clinicians.

The next step would be a case-by-case review of the patients discharged from our AAU after being referred from Practice 1 with symptoms of headache or chest pain. This would be necessarily qualitative, but would be both manageable (21 patients), and an evidence-driven place to start.

Summary

There are variations in GP referral rates across Greater Glasgow and Clyde, with some practices referring a significantly larger proportion of patients who do not require admission to hospital. However, the overall impact on total referrals from over-referring practices is small, in the order of 2% of all referrals.

Limitations

There are a couple of obvious limitations to this approach. Firstly, the best that can be hoped for by this method is to identify practices with a relatively high or low threshold for referral. This cannot tell us which threshold is right. However, it seems reasonable to expect care to be standardised across primary care, with consensus being a good guide. Therefore, practices with profligate referral patterns that veer far from the average can at least be identified as relatively risk averse.

Secondly, geographical factors come into play if the GP practice is very far from the hospital, such that same-day or ambulatory treatment may not be feasible. In these cases, admission will have more to do with practical concerns than clinical risk. It is straightforward however to identify such cases from this analysis. We have used one example of comparing closely co-located practices to remove this confounder, and there are several other examples of closely co-located practices with different referral patterns evident in our analysis.

Lastly, this method cannot identify any specific problems with referrals. It can only act as a guide to narrow down the search for helpful and unhelpful referral practices. As shown in our example, this can be turned into a manageable local project using an evidence-based approach.
